						<h1>Thomas Connelly</h1>
						<h5>Lieutenant, Engine 59</h5>
						<span class=norm>
						<strong>Age:</strong> 48<br>
						<br>
						<strong>Years on the job:</strong> 21<br>
						<br>
						<strong>What made you decide to become a Fireman?</strong><br>
						Thomas Connelly, a Lieutenant with the Chicago Fire Department credits his family especially his father with the decision to become a fireman. “Even though my father was a 				
						Chicago Fireman I never really considered that path because my father didn’t speak much about the job.”  Connelly knew he wanted to be of service to people so when the test 
						was announced in 1985 he took it as a challenge to himself.   “I came on in 1986 and when I did, my dad, who had been retired for 10 years finally wanted to talk about the 
						job!”  “My mom and dad always had a calm, selfless influence on all seven of my brothers and sisters that lives on in us today.”  “I guess you could say I am a product of my 
						wonderful family”.<br>
						<br>
						<strong>How would you like to be remembered?</strong><br>
						I’d like to be remembered as fair but competitive.  I think we should always try to put ourselves in other people’s shoes.  I try to make this my touchstone for everyday 
						living.  However, one shouldn’t mistake kindness for weakness.<br>
						<br>
						<strong>What did you want to be when you grew up?</strong><br>
						I knew I wanted to be of service to people in need. I was raised by a nurse and a fireman.  My parents were great examples of compassion.<br>
						<br>
						<strong>What’s the bravest thing you’ve ever done?</strong><br>
						I took care of my son who is deaf after my first wife died.<br>
						<br>
						<strong>When you’ve had a tough day at the firehouse what do you do to relax?</strong><br>
						Pound the heck out of racquetballs at the health club!<br>
						<br>
						<strong>What makes someone a true Chicagoan?</strong><br> 
						Someone who has a good work ethic, knows a little bit about the history of Chicago and is friendly to visitors.<br>
						<br>
						<strong>Name one thing you can’t live without?</strong><br>
						My Pocket calendar and I don’t mean a palm pilot I mean the old fashioned paper kind!<br>
						<br>
						<strong>What’s the one thing you do every day?</strong><br>
						I exercise before I shower.
